<subSubSection id="96A9393722D7077C35C4F1CD55E8AD86" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="3220301D11C02D7284CF9552716A37E0" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9EE748EE84A6B1A81C6ECBAFA0B4E5B3" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
- 
<taxonomicName id="2524A305D0055D8FF5096C72D06EA992" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Crystallina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crystallina" order="Liliales" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4F34B0972992569A91D32E8CAEBF0154" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Crystallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Lat.): refer to the species having abundant large rhomboid crystals in tube trama.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="083B79C14282C16DB81E9AECFD286459" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="22D47B3F58B71E76E4933C4F2B7623E2" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1AE416F49F32695EEB30EA326D6CDDE2" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<taxonomicName id="904A0A5CBBDD635BAB26463DDE8B6C9C" authorityName="Y. C. Dai, F. Wu, Meng Zhou &amp; Vlasak" authorityYear="2022" class="Basidiomycetes" family="Hymenochaetaceae" genus="Phylloporia" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Phylloporia crystallina" order="Hymenochaetales" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="crystallina">
<emphasis id="EC41B704D2A9601CE2FB964829EDB8A6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Phylloporia crystallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by pileate, perennial basidiomata with a thin layer of context between individual tube layers, a duplex context with a black line separating the upper tomentum and a lower compacted layer, small pores 9-10 per mm, a monomitic hyphal system, generative hyphae thin- to distinctly thick-walled with simple septa, the absence of cystidia and cystidioles, the presence of large rhomboid crystals in tube trama, broadly ellipsoid basidiospores measuring 2.8-3 
<normalizedToken id="1DFD847C4D874D0F1CEE9440A78E3EC1" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-2.3 
<normalizedToken id="D1123F6EB58B2A6A87D68B8E660E9B83" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, and growth on angiosperm stump in the Neotropics.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="313E4B19380CF0AA9C6BBEA4F0780D92" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="basidiomata">
<paragraph id="C1675132059C28C0890715586355CD96" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Basidiomata.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BEF1DE7FADBA8ABCCBBEBCB773749629" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Perennial, effused reflexed, imbricate, broadly attached to the substrate, hard corky when fresh, woody hard when dry. Pilei applanate to semi-circular, projecting up to 2 cm and 3 cm wide. Pileal surface curry yellow to cinnamon buff when fresh, become purplish chestnut when dry, concentrically sulcate with narrow zones, densely tomentum when juvenile, become velutinate to matted with age, the tomentum up to 1 mm thick, wearing off, leaving a dense trichoderm, sometime covered by mosses; margin sharp, entire. Pore surface pinkish buff to buff yellow and glancing when fresh, become honey yellow when dry; pores round, 9-10 per mm; dissepiments thin, entire. Context umber, up to 3 mm thick, duplex, with a black line separating the upper tomentum and a lower compacted layer, the upper tomentum soft corky, the lower layer hard corky. Tubes fulvous, paler than context, up to 5 mm long, distinctly stratified, usually filled a thin context among tube layers.</paragraph>
<caption id="1799B2C982BAE6F117EB5D6936420748" doi="10.3897/mycokeys.90.84767.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/693154" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
<paragraph id="5239FC3CDF9F4D7487E8A371706F0682" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="54C13C0DA254A8C822B7CE0B11058394" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Figure 2.</emphasis>
Basidiomata of 
<taxonomicName id="332E1889BB69FE023ED283322A7F7BE6" authorityName="Y. C. Dai, F. Wu, Meng Zhou &amp; Vlasak" authorityYear="2022" class="Basidiomycetes" family="Hymenochaetaceae" genus="Phylloporia" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Phylloporia crystallina" order="Hymenochaetales" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="crystallina">
<emphasis id="CC13EA3D00D45D0F90AD83BAB34CFE47" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Phylloporia crystallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(holotype, JV2106/102). Scale bar: 1 cm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption id="921DBFC3A9599460308123B4E76D9F7D" doi="10.3897/mycokeys.90.84767.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/693155" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" start="Figure 3" startId="F3">
<paragraph id="343E6EDF3C0329622489A0EBB76D72AC" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="F4026F8C08A3236EA1D4513728598B14" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Figure 3.</emphasis>
Microscopic structures of 
<taxonomicName id="15705198205F55910163F5CA2840A9C6" authorityName="Y. C. Dai, F. Wu, Meng Zhou &amp; Vlasak" authorityYear="2022" class="Basidiomycetes" family="Hymenochaetaceae" genus="Phylloporia" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Phylloporia crystallina" order="Hymenochaetales" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="crystallina">
<emphasis id="9E296B6B01977A469F643A5A263F5632" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Phylloporia crystallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(drawn from the holotype, JV2106/102). 
<emphasis id="C5BCD63F58857231AF13642E9A6A436F" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">a</emphasis>
basidiospores 
<emphasis id="34BA684A37347C7555BF6674BFC8F9C5" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">b</emphasis>
basidia and basidioles 
<emphasis id="835E7E6E9759F4B22D817E5C8553BF7E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">c</emphasis>
hyphae from upper tomentum 
<emphasis id="AB19F9EBE17D4483B7C5BC32DFBD31F3" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">d</emphasis>
hyphae from lower compacted context 
<emphasis id="038C61A36743FE2B40302E32BA1477AF" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">e</emphasis>
hyphae from dissepiment edge.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CE7B3E3E7DCE0EE25E6FF773A80AC7B3" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="hyphal structure">
<paragraph id="04905D7D8F22FDF40DF265EF46DE3956" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Hyphal structure.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="296C1A934EA2F4E1CFA5D2A7EF92DB2D" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Hyphal system monomitic; generative hyphae simple septate; tissue darkening but otherwise unchanged in the shape of the hyphae in KOH.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="82C9D5C8F3DBD309F310A73B485CB98E" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="0B9A19D4BE439DABB5713C8E56772F9D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="E16C89990B9833265E9F6642ECC39803" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Context</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Hyphae in the lower context golden yellow, fairly thick-walled with a wide lumen, unbranched, frequently simple-septate, loosely interwoven, slightly CB+, 3-5 
<normalizedToken id="AD252F6F6B775E8389F05C86D63D79A4" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
diam.; hyphae in the upper tomentum yellow, fairly thick-walled with a wide lumen, unbranched, frequently simple septate, straight, regularly arranged, 5-7 
<normalizedToken id="49023A638190F7C6FAAD71C6C8983051" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
diam.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B7839542FA0646D9E4E5671CB6D334AA" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="106021E7E6415109EA21BAA5AB64EF27" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="9BBDC333153C4CA215C398A0645865B1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Tubes</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Tramal hyphae hyaline to yellow, thin- to thick-walled with a narrow to medium lumen, rarely branched, frequently to occasionally simple septate, flexuous, loosely interwoven, slightly CB+, 2-3.5 
<normalizedToken id="68A6827BD1B6B04E4CFBBBE78125E303" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
diam.; hyphae at dissepiment edges smooth; large rhomboid crystals abundant among tube trama.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1C2AE2B48026D2D2E886571AB5A792C6" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="A4CB34D708D662B12807D832DFED3FE6" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis id="D4F127AC53DB6990E97A00E2E67F5DFD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Hymenium</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Cystidia and cystidioles absent; basidia barrel-shaped with four sterigmata and a simple septum at the base, 5-7 
<normalizedToken id="5E2AF82B6C52F96828D79D41BE3E61CB" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3.5-4 
<normalizedToken id="BA419ABB22ECD2871EDAD61977088DD3" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
. Basidioles similar to basidia in shape, but slightly smaller. Basidiospores broadly ellipsoid to subglobose, yellowish, thick-walled, smooth, not collapsed, IKI-, CB-, (2.7-) 2.8-3 (-3.1) 
<normalizedToken id="F373B728093A0FB016A8CA0DCEFCE426" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-2.3 (-2.4) 
<normalizedToken id="989DF94496AD719B9A4EFFDE3F2D332C" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, L = 2.9 
<normalizedToken id="F86DEF5289CF381789F70CD1A139E97F" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, W = 2.1 
<normalizedToken id="E4CCB481CDECA562148535549B0ADEEE" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, Q = 1.38 (n = 30/1).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F4888BFE24BFEE9E143ECE64E4365063" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" type="notes">
<paragraph id="79919553604F9AEAEE03FFF9B5523199" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C2971E5C7E5350EE3B57335F01F1B15" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
Phylogenetically (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="93CA27AE180C8DF14B7E410DF15483D7" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Phylogeny of Phylloporia inferred from the 28 S dataset. The topology is from the ML analysis, and the support values from ML (former) and BI (latter) analyses simultaneously greater than or equal to 50 % and 0.90 are indicated at the nodes, respectively. The new species are in boldface." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.90.84767.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/693153" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">1</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="72778779EEB8EC1279E422364A58A28A" authorityName="Y. C. Dai, F. Wu, Meng Zhou &amp; Vlasak" authorityYear="2022" class="Basidiomycetes" family="Hymenochaetaceae" genus="Phylloporia" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Phylloporia crystallina" order="Hymenochaetales" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="crystallina">
<emphasis id="B5D2180473FB4A774D76624CB445DB8E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Phylloporia crystallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is related to 
<taxonomicName id="6A36269F5934B5D84388F40AB0C76822" genus="P." lsidName="P. montana" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis id="B2E266F57C0F090E888C4D504DCE8495" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Oliveira-Filho &amp; Gibertoni (
<bibRefCitation id="20AB9F0FE1D5CC4C4F0D80C391979F84" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-019-01476-4" author="Wu, F" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Progress" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="615 - 639" refId="B31" refString="Wu, F, Ren, GJ, Wang, L, Oliveira-Filho, JRC, Gibertoni, TB, Dai, YC, 2019. An updated phylogeny and diversity of Phylloporia (Hymenochaetales): Eight new species and keys to species of the genus. Mycological Progress 18 (5): 615 - 639, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-019-01476-4" title="An updated phylogeny and diversity of Phylloporia (Hymenochaetales): Eight new species and keys to species of the genus." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-019-01476-4" volume="18" year="2019">Wu et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName id="481C15475845DA548F8DC09E10901039" genus="P." lsidName="P. montana" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis id="AA2816A3A1C9ABFDA7F68CA331CB60C4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has wider pores (3-5 per mm vs. 9-10 per mm) and larger and cylindrical basidiospores (4-5 
<normalizedToken id="5E81D3016AE73F810AE9ECA3E5D1F2DB" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3 
<normalizedToken id="826F12A6F6297ADEC567058A0DEA5D54" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
vs. 2.8-3 
<normalizedToken id="073FD53D1311DFA4DB00D69B948E1A85" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-2.3 
<normalizedToken id="F766D61E5053A9A0DCB9CC57CF7F6A67" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="A22041B7D4BE44B737F8C137705E2712" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-019-01476-4" author="Wu, F" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Progress" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="615 - 639" refId="B31" refString="Wu, F, Ren, GJ, Wang, L, Oliveira-Filho, JRC, Gibertoni, TB, Dai, YC, 2019. An updated phylogeny and diversity of Phylloporia (Hymenochaetales): Eight new species and keys to species of the genus. Mycological Progress 18 (5): 615 - 639, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-019-01476-4" title="An updated phylogeny and diversity of Phylloporia (Hymenochaetales): Eight new species and keys to species of the genus." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s11557-019-01476-4" volume="18" year="2019">Wu et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName id="28D58072623C1C21AF5D600C90706BFF" genus="P." lsidName="P. crystallina" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="crystallina">
<emphasis id="DEA956D85E4486DE10ABCBFC6B621784" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. crystallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="11040B53DF8153E78E62195E3063D0FE" genus="P." lsidName="P. crataegi" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="crataegi">
<emphasis id="3C4713214A3932CDDB6A8C12D1185288" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. crataegi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L.W. Zhou &amp; Y.C. Dai by sharing perennial and pileate basidiomata with duplex context, a monomitic hyphal system, interwoven tramal hyphae, the absence of cystidia and cystidioles, and broadly ellipsoid to subglobose basidiospores (
<bibRefCitation id="7CF0490321D507C5D5D141EE12266F06" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/11-093" author="Zhou, LW" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="211 - 222" refId="B35" refString="Zhou, LW, Dai, YC, 2012. Phylogeny and taxonomy of Phylloporia (Hymenochaetales): New species and a worldwide key to the genus. Mycologia 104 (1): 211 - 222, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/11-093" title="Phylogeny and taxonomy of Phylloporia (Hymenochaetales): New species and a worldwide key to the genus." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/11-093" volume="104" year="2012">Zhou and Dai 2012</bibRefCitation>
). However, the latter species differs from 
<taxonomicName id="FC9C88BC65D53688CA7C5B51B8573C2F" genus="P." lsidName="P. crystallina" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="crystallina">
<emphasis id="7460D3F1D9A1664199F3C10050743CDE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. crystallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of rhomboid crystals, distinctly longer basidia (8-11 
<normalizedToken id="18BA9E8D172C58A71F8BE4327E17F8D3" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
vs. 5-7 
<normalizedToken id="A01EC4FC705AA5CA61115377CE6AE452" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
), and growth on living 
<taxonomicName id="EC173CCD36CA125A097FFA470C5FCC16" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D85763B28900552CED44A49FA34EA40A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Crataegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in temperate China (
<bibRefCitation id="32CB7CAE835FEFA21128E0177F36F5BA" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/11-093" author="Zhou, LW" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="211 - 222" refId="B35" refString="Zhou, LW, Dai, YC, 2012. Phylogeny and taxonomy of Phylloporia (Hymenochaetales): New species and a worldwide key to the genus. Mycologia 104 (1): 211 - 222, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/11-093" title="Phylogeny and taxonomy of Phylloporia (Hymenochaetales): New species and a worldwide key to the genus." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/11-093" volume="104" year="2012">Zhou and Dai 2012</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, 
<taxonomicName id="DF813E52A3236266CDA89CD109E88FA7" genus="P." lsidName="P. crystallina" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="crystallina">
<emphasis id="08D7AA7784525CA2D29D31229D457E42" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. crystallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E9C640F897F39008F145FDA7C5C9FD52" genus="P." lsidName="P. crataegi" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="crataegi">
<emphasis id="84479409CE21B259B4FC2D3A907D807F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. crataegi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are phylogenetically distantly related (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6C813E8F6F574E8AE6A8A4F52617EFD3" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Phylogeny of Phylloporia inferred from the 28 S dataset. The topology is from the ML analysis, and the support values from ML (former) and BI (latter) analyses simultaneously greater than or equal to 50 % and 0.90 are indicated at the nodes, respectively. The new species are in boldface." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.90.84767.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/693153" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">1</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="344D54A6BDE7DC5023ADEB220B09659D" genus="P." lsidName="P. chrysites" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="chrysites">
<emphasis id="2547988B505A79B443DF526CB3A68F41" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. chrysites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Berk.) Ryvarden is a Neotropical species. It has similar basidiospores as 
<taxonomicName id="44A8E67DACC5E7E1D5C39FE4C36C2AD6" genus="P." lsidName="P. crystallina" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="crystallina">
<emphasis id="AF1C4CABA44A7AF7BF14A87BD75C097C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. crystallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the former is readily distinguished from the latter by its annual habit and larger pores (9-10 per mm vs. pores 6-8 per mm, 
<bibRefCitation id="C749ED7E84589D7C307112BFF36D7908" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-021-00496-4" author="Wu, F" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="1 - 192" refId="B32" refString="Wu, F, Zhou, LW, Vlasak, J, Dai, YC, 2022. Global diversity and systematics of Hymenochaetaceae with poroid hymenophore. Fungal Diversity 113 (1): 1 - 192, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-021-00496-4" title="Global diversity and systematics of Hymenochaetaceae with poroid hymenophore." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-021-00496-4" volume="113" year="2022">Wu et al. 2022</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="388AA28EF934F39615985274B966FA4A" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">
<taxonomicName id="E8A3F81931905589B26629E685BD792C" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Polyporaceae" genus="Trametes" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Trametes lilliputiana" order="Polyporales" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="lilliputiana">
<emphasis id="DCA5197C6CC17FF8D29FFA1F970E26E9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Trametes lilliputiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Speg. and 
<taxonomicName id="A5A96CB901FE5A4E291960E6F4A15E8C" class="Basidiomycetes" family="Hymenochaetaceae" genus="Pyropolyporus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Pyropolyporus subpectinatus" order="Hymenochaetales" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="subpectinatus">
<emphasis id="761CC984B841685681D0CB34A1547392" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Pyropolyporus subpectinatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Murrill were originally described from Brazil and Cuba, respectively (
<bibRefCitation id="579DCCB6D8F460EFB82124267F42BC9B" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.3624" author="Spegazzini, C" journalOrPublisher="Boletin de la Academia Nacional de Ciencias en Cordoba" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="381 - 622" refId="B25" refString="Spegazzini, C, 1889. Fungi Puiggariani. Pugillus 1. Boletin de la Academia Nacional de Ciencias en Cordoba 11: 381 - 622, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.3624" title="Fungi Puiggariani. Pugillus 1." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.3624" volume="11" year="1889">Spegazzini 1889</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="5CA1A40A64F6CCA67D07FB2E6B12A6D0" author="Murrill, WA" journalOrPublisher="North American Flora" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="73 - 131" refId="B13" refString="Murrill, WA, 1908. Polyporaceae 2. North American Flora 9 (2): 73 - 131" title="Polyporaceae 2." volume="9" year="1908">Murrill 1908</bibRefCitation>
), and they were treated as synonyms of 
<taxonomicName id="5661C0CA409C34E5F20E00C3AF58CB57" class="Basidiomycetes" family="Hymenochaetaceae" genus="Phylloporia" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Phylloporia pectinata" order="Hymenochaetales" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="pectinata">
<emphasis id="A2AF8BF557DFE21576D0796358F87A86" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Phylloporia pectinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Klotzsch) Ryvarden (
<bibRefCitation id="AEDB77B67F382FC927BA5C5384A74F1E" author="Bresadola, G" journalOrPublisher="Hedwigia" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="46 - 80" refId="B3" refString="Bresadola, G, 1912. Basidiomycetes Philippinenses 2. Hedwigia 53: 46 - 80" title="Basidiomycetes Philippinenses 2." volume="53" year="1912">Bresadola 1912</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="08E739ED5A90D6FB0D27C2A4194E0FD1" author="Ryvarden, L" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="169 - 198" refId="B21" refString="Ryvarden, L, 1985. Type studies in the Polyporaceae 17. Species described by W.A. Murrill. Mycotaxon 23: 169 - 198" title="Type studies in the Polyporaceae 17. Species described by W. A. Murrill." volume="23" year="1985">Ryvarden 1985</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="ED7F68188DA0D0916E95F235A42980B6" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1987.12025704" author="Rajchenberg, M" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="246 - 464" refId="B17" refString="Rajchenberg, M, Wright, JE, 1987. Type studies of Corticiaceae and Polyporaceae (Aphyllophorales) described by C. Spegazzini. Mycologia 79 (2): 246 - 464, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1987.12025704" title="Type studies of Corticiaceae and Polyporaceae (Aphyllophorales) described by C. Spegazzini." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1987.12025704" volume="79" year="1987">Rajchenberg and Wright 1987</bibRefCitation>
). However, these two taxa may be different from 
<taxonomicName id="1B49FAFF9185EC0374536F01273918B7" class="Basidiomycetes" family="Hymenochaetaceae" genus="Phylloporia" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Phylloporia pectinata" order="Hymenochaetales" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="pectinata">
<emphasis id="CAE094E460B21261E0DC48BF2FB59931" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">Phylloporia pectinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because its type locality is in India (
<bibRefCitation id="941666A169799830854A150E4F6EE37C" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-021-00496-4" author="Wu, F" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="1 - 192" refId="B32" refString="Wu, F, Zhou, LW, Vlasak, J, Dai, YC, 2022. Global diversity and systematics of Hymenochaetaceae with poroid hymenophore. Fungal Diversity 113 (1): 1 - 192, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-021-00496-4" title="Global diversity and systematics of Hymenochaetaceae with poroid hymenophore." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-021-00496-4" volume="113" year="2022">Wu et al. 2022</bibRefCitation>
). The type of 
<taxonomicName id="0D7B0A41A65231C3746112AA2CEDFEA2" genus="T." lsidName="T. lilliputiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="lilliputiana">
<emphasis id="B64E83AA12A93243A8A05FDFA1AF0019" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">T. lilliputiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sterile, but its pilei are confluent and thin, and its upper surface is smooth according to its original description (
<bibRefCitation id="5EC3F4F7EDAA9F31558DFFA80495ACF8" DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.3624" author="Spegazzini, C" journalOrPublisher="Boletin de la Academia Nacional de Ciencias en Cordoba" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="381 - 622" refId="B25" refString="Spegazzini, C, 1889. Fungi Puiggariani. Pugillus 1. Boletin de la Academia Nacional de Ciencias en Cordoba 11: 381 - 622, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.3624" title="Fungi Puiggariani. Pugillus 1." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.3624" volume="11" year="1889">Spegazzini 1889</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="3BE50701F7980351448E982750613479" genus="P." lsidName="P. subpectinatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="subpectinatus">
<emphasis id="99F3846B306D3CC6F8B7B8251E2323A2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. subpectinatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has globose basidiospores (
<bibRefCitation id="B91D794BEAB7F74C87159AD2D2569374" author="Murrill, WA" journalOrPublisher="North American Flora" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="73 - 131" refId="B13" refString="Murrill, WA, 1908. Polyporaceae 2. North American Flora 9 (2): 73 - 131" title="Polyporaceae 2." volume="9" year="1908">Murrill 1908</bibRefCitation>
). So, these two taxa are closer or identical to 
<taxonomicName id="8C9CDE0F456287AF68B079A3FC2AC2DA" genus="P." lsidName="P. pectinata" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="pectinata">
<emphasis id="A2B4FB98E0BDE351316F4B7AD0BA4520" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. pectinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which has a dimitic hyphal structure and globose basidiospores (
<bibRefCitation id="61DD4A4352B264434E3667A3250BA867" author="Ryvarden, L" journalOrPublisher="Synopsis Fungorum" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" pagination="1 - 227" refId="B22" refString="Ryvarden, L, 2004. Neotropical polypores 1. Introduction, Hymenochaetaceae and Ganodermataceae. Synopsis Fungorum 19: 1 - 227" title="Neotropical polypores 1. Introduction, Hymenochaetaceae and Ganodermataceae." volume="19" year="2004">Ryvarden 2004</bibRefCitation>
); while 
<taxonomicName id="44BBDF74BDF38A55CC80C38D500AB635" genus="P." lsidName="P. crystallina" pageId="0" pageNumber="71" rank="species" species="crystallina">
<emphasis id="7ADABCBD9A9EA2B8874F2A2F4214BF3A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="71">P. crystallina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a monomitic hyphal system and broadly ellipsoid basidiospores.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
